description: From Middle English fesen (“to drive, incite, put into action; frighten, terrify, prosecute, punish”), from Old English fēsan, fȳsan (“to hasten, impel”), from Proto-Germanic *funsijaną (“to make ready”).

verbs.description: feaze (third-person singular simple present feazes, present participle feazing, simple past and past participle feazed)

examples: 1911,  Graham B. Forbes,  The Boys of Columbia High on the River‎[1], page 12:There's mighty little that feazes you.
